    text: `Overpopulation happens when the number of people in a particular area or on the planet grows so large that the environment and available resources struggle to support everyone. This situation puts immense pressure on natural resources, such as water, food, and energy, which are essential for human survival. As the human population keeps increasing, more resources are needed to meet the basic needs of people. However, many of these resources, like freshwater, land, and fossil fuels, are finite, meaning they can run out if used too quickly or irresponsibly. When too many people rely on the same limited resources, it leads to their overuse, which can cause long-term damage to the environment. One of the biggest problems caused by overpopulation is the depletion of freshwater. Water is essential for drinking, growing crops, and for everyday tasks like cooking and cleaning. However, as the population grows, more water is needed to meet the needs of everyone. This means that rivers, lakes, and underground water sources are being drained faster than they can be naturally replenished. In many places around the world, people are already facing water shortages, and overpopulation makes this issue even worse. As the demand for water rises, conflicts over access to clean water become more common, and the environment suffers as water bodies dry up or become polluted. Another major consequence of overpopulation is the increased demand for food. As more people are born, more land must be used for farming to grow enough food to feed everyone. This often leads to the clearing of forests and natural habitats to make room for agriculture, which causes the loss of biodiversity. Many animals and plants that once thrived in these areas are forced to find new homes, and some species even face extinction because they can no longer survive in the altered environment. Additionally, the heavy use of fertilizers, pesticides, and water for farming contributes to soil degradation, water pollution, and a decrease in the quality of the land over time. As the global population grows, so does the challenge of producing enough food in a`
